      <h3><a name="Thursday, May 19, 2005" href="#Thursday, May 19, 2005">
          <font color="#660000">Thursday, May 19, 2005</font></a></h3>
   	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="111656320804861788"></a>
    
    <h2><font color="#000080"><!-- 2004-08-31 -->
    
    Sorting the Mail: Agile Databases, Vulnerable Applications, and Optimized Code
    
    </font></h2>
    
    
    <p>
	<p><a href="http://www.acm.org/technews/articles/2005-7/0518w.html#item1">ACM News Service: Quick Picks.</a>&nbsp; I don&rsquo;t have time to dig into these deeper, but I don&rsquo;t want to lose them, either:</p><ul><li>&ldquo;<a href="http://www.acm.org/technews/articles/2005-7/0518w.html#item17">Join the Evolution</a>&rdquo; &mdash; Scott Ambler&rsquo;s invitation to &ldquo;Agile Database Techniques.&rdquo; I&rsquo;m interested in the modeling, refactoring, and coupling issues.&nbsp; I&rsquo;m also curious how much business entities are able to adhere to the problem space rather than be solution-space artifacts.</li><li>&ldquo;<a href="http://www.acm.org/technews/articles/2005-7/0518w.html#item15">Developers&rsquo; Growing Challenge</a>&rdquo; &mdash; Peter Coffee&rsquo;s eWeek article on the problems of vulnerabilities in line-of-business applications and how developers are ill-equipped to deal with it and soon tools will make it harder.&nbsp; Now there&rsquo;s a challenge for simplifying rather than covering over fragile complexity.</li><li>&ldquo;<a href="http://www.acm.org/technews/articles/2005-7/0518w.html#item5">Researchers Speed, Optimize Code With New Open Source Tools</a>&rdquo; &mdash; This is about optimization of computer codes for certain large-scale computations.&nbsp; It would be interesting to see how generic this is and what its domain of application could turn out to be.&nbsp; (This goes deep in my files, but filed it is.)</li></ul><p><em></em></p>
    </p>
